<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,1710,1896]" lastBlockId="6.[264,1323,284,910]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">
Egyptian specimens correspond with 
<emphasis box="[753,885,1711,1736]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">V. b i v i rg a t a</emphasis>
Austen ­ 
<typeStatus box="[1006,1109,1710,1736]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
female in 
<collectionCode box="[1235,1323,1710,1736]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">BMNH</collectionCode>
(
<collectingCountry box="[272,384,1750,1776]" name="Palestine" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Palestine</collectingCountry>
: Athlit, 
<date box="[481,615,1750,1776]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" value="1920-07-25">
<number box="[481,511,1750,1776]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" value="25.0">25</number>
.vii. 
<number box="[552,615,1750,1776]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" value="1920.0">1920</number>
</date>
(Captain P.J. Barraud) examined. The male genitalia are as illustrated for a specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[630,771,1791,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgata">
<emphasis box="[630,771,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">V. bivirgata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[855,1015,1790,1816]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Greathead" box="[1036,1242,1790,1816]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" refString="Greathead, D. J. (1980) Insects of Saudi Arabia. Diptera: Fam. Bombyliidae. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 2, 291 - 337." type="journal article" year="1980">
Greathead, 
<number box="[1179,1242,1790,1816]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Villa bivirgata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also a common species in 
<collectingCountry box="[726,804,1830,1856]" name="Jordan" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Jordan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Arabyat" box="[821,1063,1830,1856]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" refString="Arabyat, S., Katbeh-Bader, A. &amp; Greathead, D. (2004) The bee flies (Diptera: Bombyliidae) of Jordan. Zootaxa, 654, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="2004">
Arabyat et al., 
<number box="[1003,1063,1830,1856]" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) as well as 
<collectingCountry box="[1208,1318,1830,1856]" name="Palestine" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Palestine</collectingCountry>
. Thus the Egyptian species is 
<taxonomicName box="[605,740,1871,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgata">
<emphasis box="[605,740,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">V. bivirgata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is clearly distinct from both 
<taxonomicName box="[1128,1272,1871,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ventruosa">
<emphasis box="[1128,1272,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">V. ventruosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[264,357,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">V. l a e v i s</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[375,543,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgata">
<emphasis box="[375,543,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Villa bivirgata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName box="[864,949,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cana">
<emphasis box="[864,949,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">V. cana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs most notably from it in not having the black scale bands on the abdominal tergites reaching the sides of the tergites; in not having distinct black scale tufts at the sides of tergites 
<number box="[1122,1168,364,390]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
, although in some specimens there may be one or two black scales; in not having very dark blackish legs with greyish scales but brown legs and ochreous scales; antennal flagellum not conical at base and gradually tapering; in having a more rounded, less elongate and not parallel sided abdomen. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[735,808,524,550]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 6" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[374,1176,520,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[332,1284,504,1593]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 6. Male genitalia: 3. V. aegyptiaca Engel, lateral view; 4. V. bivirgata Austen: a. lateral view, b. tip of epiphallus; 5. V. cana Meigen: a. lateral view, b. tip of epiphallus; 6. V. micrargyra (Walker), lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171553/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[790,808,524,550]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
